    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2557987175" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2557987175" />
    <a title="Adarsh Chauhan" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/30211354-adarsh-chauhan"><img alt="Adarsh Chauhan" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1632250369p2/30211354.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2557987175?book_show_action=true">Oct 15, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Adarsh Chauhan" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Adarsh Chauhan" href="/user/show/30211354-adarsh-chauhan">Adarsh Chauhan</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2557987175" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13187536096597906701">I feel that I keep coming back to Marquez&apos;s melancholy-soaked stories time and again because I have not found any other author whose stories have that indelible impression and evocation of sorrowful sympathy as much as Marquez&apos;s. The short stories in this collection have less of his realist magical aspects than his other usual novel stories but it possesses the same unique quality in terms of conjuring and delivery. Reading one after the other, the readers gets the harmony of the short compositi</span>
  <span id="freeText13187536096597906701" style="display:none">I feel that I keep coming back to Marquez's melancholy-soaked stories time and again because I have not found any other author whose stories have that indelible impression and evocation of sorrowful sympathy as much as Marquez's. The short stories in this collection have less of his realist magical aspects than his other usual novel stories but it possesses the same unique quality in terms of conjuring and delivery. Reading one after the other, the readers gets the harmony of the short compositions and see the bigger picture - the experience of foreignness that one finds himself in when put far away in lands unknown and different from one's origins and memories. The stories here complete the mosaic of this experience with sorrowfulness, paranoia, pitifulness, uncertainty, and despite everything, tenacity and a feeling of moving on. The predicaments that his characters usually find themselves in even evoke a sympathetic humour and I somehow remembered lines (not exact) from Heinlein's <i>Stranger in a Strange Land</i> (may be triggered by the keyword 'stranger') while reading this book:<br /><br />“<i>I've found out why people laugh. They laugh because it hurts so much . . . because it's the only thing that'll make it stop hurting.</i>”<br /><br />Probably Marquez aims at achieving this reflection in the readers through humour by creating characters who are victims of some times their circumstances, and at other times, of their own shortcomings. My favourite stories from this collection were: "María dos Prazeres", "The Trail of Your Blood in the Snow", "I Only Came To Use The Phone" and "The Saint". Marquez is undoubtedly an important author of fiction with a beauty in writing influenced by his Latin American origins.<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="13187536096597906701" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

