  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1755668575?book_show_action=true">Oct 03, 2016</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Amrita Saju" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Amrita Saju" href="/user/show/46596337-amrita-saju">Amrita Saju</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1755668575" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12136662698126316044">I started reading &apos;Strange Pilgrims&apos; because I simply loved &apos;Love in the time of cholera&apos; and was hoping to get another such read from Marquez. Yes, it&apos;s very similarly intense, but most of these stories are so depressing, especially the last one titled &apos;The Trail of Your Blood in the Snow&apos;, I didn&apos;t want it to end that way. Not that I don&apos;t enjoy that kind of writing, where even a tragedy is very beautiful to read, but I just wanted a happy ending. Is it too much to ask for that? <br/>In most of my </span>
  <span id="freeText12136662698126316044" style="display:none">I started reading 'Strange Pilgrims' because I simply loved 'Love in the time of cholera' and was hoping to get another such read from Marquez. Yes, it's very similarly intense, but most of these stories are so depressing, especially the last one titled 'The Trail of Your Blood in the Snow', I didn't want it to end that way. Not that I don't enjoy that kind of writing, where even a tragedy is very beautiful to read, but I just wanted a happy ending. Is it too much to ask for that? <br />In most of my previous experiences (though very few), I've found how short stories are always more sadder, intense and some so metaphorical that I don't understand them at all. I would like to attribute this incomprehensible state of my mind to the limited exposure I have to such intense writings. There was one such story in this book too that I found absolutely indecipherable; it was titled 'Light is like Water'. Someday I hope someone can take me through Marquez's point on that piece of writing.<br />This obviously won't stop me from wanting to read more of the author's works, because even though not a very interesting one, this was certainly a 'rich in vocabulary', 'enriched in deeper emotions' kind of a read.</span>
  <a data-text-id="12136662698126316044" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


