    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_149388084" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/149388084" />
    <a title="Stephanie" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/245640-stephanie"><img alt="Stephanie" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1618252490p2/245640.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/149388084?book_show_action=true">Feb 20, 2011</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Stephanie" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Stephanie" href="/user/show/245640-stephanie">Stephanie</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780140239409" href="/book/show/452153.Strange_Pilgrims">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer149388084" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer3034921762109272171">After the short story &quot;The Handsomest Drowned Man in the World,&quot; which has been an enchanting but brief introduction to Marquez, _Strange Pilgrims_ is my first real encounter with his writing, which is a steady-handed mix of precision and warmth. His story-telling is urbane, evoking a 20th century past nether-world in which what for a sub-urban American is strangeness (the migrating pain of an ousted president-in-exile, the weightless body of a saint, a woman who makes a living by selling her dr</span>
  <span id="freeText3034921762109272171" style="display:none">After the short story "The Handsomest Drowned Man in the World," which has been an enchanting but brief introduction to Marquez, _Strange Pilgrims_ is my first real encounter with his writing, which is a steady-handed mix of precision and warmth. His story-telling is urbane, evoking a 20th century past nether-world in which what for a sub-urban American is strangeness (the migrating pain of an ousted president-in-exile, the weightless body of a saint, a woman who makes a living by selling her dreams, an endearing little dog who has been trained to cry) that seems totally natural--his "magical realism," but maybe only for the blockheaded reader (me as well) will it be more magical than real. The characters are all alluring, each for different reasons, but all because they are one with the realities of their stories. The atmosphere of each city--Geneva, Rome, Barcelona, Madrid, Paris, etc.--is rendered in its beauty and stench with dispassionate reverie. The author occasionally but very naturally intervenes to mention where he picked up the story or even to relate an interaction with his characters, situating himself as one of them, even as he writes about himself in a kind of disguise. All of it adds to a sum of measured skill, a trustworthy story-teller, and, for me, the best kind of reading.</span>
  <a data-text-id="3034921762109272171" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


